## Detection Rules

### Rule 1 — Duplicate Diagnosis with Date Discrepancy (Severity: High, AC-2)
Match diagnoses by:
- Identical or equivalent ICD-10 code (e.g., E11 and E11.9 are the same condition).
- Identical or semantically equivalent normalised description (e.g., "Type 2 diabetes mellitus" and "T2DM").

When a match is found across two or more different source documents:
- Report the pair with both `extracted_data_id` values.
- Include the recorded dates from each entry in `reasoning` (no PII — dates only).
- Set `conflict_type: "DuplicateDiagnosis"` and `severity: "High"`.

### Rule 2 — Conflicting Diagnosis Status (Severity: High)
Flag when the same condition appears as "active" in one document and "resolved", "remission", or "history of" in another.
This represents a clinical inconsistency that could affect treatment decisions.
Set `conflict_type: "ConflictingDiagnosis"` and `severity: "High"`.

### Rule 3 — Mutually Exclusive Conditions (Severity: High)
Flag when two diagnoses that cannot clinically coexist simultaneously are both recorded as active
(e.g., "no known diabetes" and active E11 code; or hyper- and hypothyroidism active simultaneously).
Set `conflict_type: "ConflictingDiagnosis"` and `severity: "High"`.

## Source Citation Requirements (AIR-007)

For each detected conflict you MUST provide:
- `data_point_a_id`: `extracted_data_id` of the first diagnosis entry.
- `data_point_b_id`: `extracted_data_id` of the conflicting second entry.
- `additional_source_ids`: array of any additional `extracted_data_id` values when 3+ documents share the conflict (Edge Case).

Both `data_point_a_id` and `data_point_b_id` must reference valid UUIDs from the data below;
do not fabricate IDs.

## Output Rules

- Call `analyze_clinical_conflicts` exactly once.
- Analyse ONLY diagnosis data points; ignore medications and procedure dates in this pass.
- Return `conflicts_detected: false` with an empty `conflicts` array if no diagnosis conflicts exist.
- Do NOT include patient names, contact information, or other PII in `reasoning`.
- Use only ICD-10 codes, normalised diagnosis names, and clinical status terms in descriptions.
- Assign `confidence` per conflict: 0.95–1.00 = identical ICD code confirmed across docs; 0.75–0.94 = highly similar descriptions; 0.50–0.74 = possible semantic match.
- Suppress conflicts with `confidence < 0.50`.
- Sort results: High severity first, then Medium.
